  "response": "The smallest known type of black hole is called a stellar black hole, which typically forms when a massive star collapses. These can be around 10-100 times the mass of our Sun, with a diameter of about 30-300 kilometers.\n\nHowever, theoretical \"quantum\" or \"micro\" black holes could potentially be much smaller. These hypothetical black holes would be extremely tiny, potentially as small as the Planck length (about 10^-35 meters), but would require immense energy to create and have not been observed.\n\nThe most compact known black holes are stellar black holes, which are still relatively large compared to atomic scales. In practice, creating an extremely small black hole would require concentrating an enormous amount of mass in an incredibly tiny space.",
